58%2C0%2C53.999996948242%2C100\u0026amp;w=2400\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003eBased on the classic hook and ring game, \u003cem\u003eHUNT(er/ed)\u003c/em\u003e by Meghan Cross and Dillin Apelyan has two players take opposing roles of hunter and monster. Players roll 2d6 each, competing to see who can roll doubles first to advance their token across the board. The winner then pulls a card with a corresponding prompt, pushing the story forward in the same tradition as games like \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/tabletop-games/24161224/for-the-queen-second-edition-changes-darrington-press-descended-games\"\u003eFor The Queen\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e. The solo iteration of the game takes \u003cem\u003eHUNTER(er/ed)\u003c/em\u003e’s core experience of examining monstrosity and pushes the player to move along a scale of acceptance or denial. A stretch goal for \u003cem\u003eHUNT(er/ed)\u003c/em\u003e’s crowdfunding campaign, the solo rule set was written by Elliot Davis who has written his own solo game, \u003cem\u003eProject Ecco\u003c/em\u003e, as well as solo editions of Soul Muppet’s \u003cem\u003eOrbital Blues\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem\u003ePaint the Town Red\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://platform.polygon.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/yorp0v92.png?quality=90\u0026amp;strip=all\u0026amp;crop=0,0,100,100\" data-pswp-height=\"720\" data-pswp-width=\"1280\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"A top-down photo of cards for the board game The Zone laid out on a table\" data-chromatic=\"ignore\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-nimg=\"fill\" sizes=\"(max-width: 639px) 100vw, (max-width: 1023px) 50vw, 700px\" srcset=\"https://platform.polygon.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/yorp0v92.png?quality=90\u0026amp;strip=all\u0026amp;crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100\u0026amp;w=256 256w, https://platform.polygon.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/